⛄️⛄️⛄️ Do these snowman need a little refresh? 

I’m thinking about an update with “stretch it” “catch it” and “map it” “tap it.” Would you like to see those options added?

Here’s what we do for the current routine: 
❄️ read it - say the word 
❄️ spell it- say each letter
❄️ tell it - whisper the letters to a partner
❄️ clap it - clap for each letter
❄️ snap it - snap (or tap knees) for each letter 
❄️ write it - write the word on a dry erase board or on the carpet with your finger
❄️ cheer it - cheer each letter 
❄️ disappear it - erase the word one letter at a time from left to right

Have you played It’s Snowing Sight Words yet?? ☃️ 

Here’s how you play:
❄️ Set out a set of sight word cards and grab some snowballs (aka cotton balls or white pom poms)
❄️ Tell one student a word or word feature to find. It might sound like this…
“Put a snowball on a word that begins with the /long i/ sound” or “Put a snowball on a word that rhymes with “moon.”
❄️ The student tosses or places a snowball on the word and everyone writes the word on the recording page. 

This activity helps students analyze words to improve their reading and writing! 💙

We know MOVEMENT enhances LEARNING! I’m sharing a fun way to squeeze some extra movement into your day! 🤩

Move Maker has all the fun and benefits of Simon Says, but no one is ever out! (If you were a kid like me, being caught making a mistake was never enjoyable.) Here’s how you play:

1. One child is the Move Maker. They choose 3-6 movement cards to put in the template. 
2. Everyone does the movements. You can do them once or several times like a little workout circuit. 
3. The Move Maker picks someone who was doing their best to come up and select new cards.

You can play as many times as you like. That makes the activity perfect for transitions, brain breaks, morning meeting, or inside recess!
